@page "/docs"

<PageTitle>Getting Started - GuideFlow Docs</PageTitle>

<div class="docs-content">
    <h1>Getting Started</h1>
    <p class="docs-lead">
        GuideFlow is a Blazor component library for building accessible, animated guided tours.
        Install the NuGet package, register the service, and create your first tour in under 2 minutes.
    </p>

    <h2 id="installation">
        Install via NuGet
        <a class="docs-anchor" href="#installation">#</a>
    </h2>

    <p>Run the following command in your project directory:</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="bash" Code="dotnet add package GuideFlow" />

    <p>Or install via the NuGet Package Manager:</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="powershell" Code="Install-Package GuideFlow" />

    <h2 id="setup">
        Setup
        <a class="docs-anchor" href="#setup">#</a>
    </h2>

    <h3 id="register-service">Register the Service</h3>

    <p>In your <code>Program.cs</code>, add the GuideFlow service:</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="csharp" Code="@(@"using GuideFlow.Services;

var builder = WebAssemblyHostBuilder.CreateDefault(args);
// ... other registrations

builder.Services.AddGuideFlow();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();")" />

    <div class="docs-note docs-note--info">
        <strong>💡 Server-Side Blazor</strong>
        For Blazor Server projects, use <code>builder.Services.AddGuideFlow()</code> in your <code>Program.cs</code> the same way.
        GuideFlow supports both WebAssembly and Server hosting models.
    </div>

    <h3 id="add-css">Add the CSS and JS</h3>

    <p>Reference the GuideFlow stylesheet and JS module in your <code>index.html</code> (WebAssembly) or <code>_Host.cshtml</code> (Server):</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="html" Code="@(@"<link href=""_content/GuideFlow/guideflow.css"" rel=""stylesheet"" />
<script src=""_content/GuideFlow/guideflow.module.js""></script>")" />

    <h3 id="import-namespaces">Import Namespaces</h3>

    <p>Add these namespaces to your <code>_Imports.razor</code>:</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="razor" Code="@(@"@using GuideFlow.Components
@using GuideFlow.Enums
@using GuideFlow.Models
@using GuideFlow.Services")" />

    <h2 id="first-tour">
        Your First Tour
        <a class="docs-anchor" href="#first-tour">#</a>
    </h2>

    <p>Wrap your page content with <code>GuideFlowTour</code> and add steps:</p>

    <CodeBlock Language="razor" Code="@(@"<button id=""step1"" @onclick=""StartTour"">Start Tour</button>
<button id=""step2"">Another element</button>

<GuideFlowTour @ref=""tour"" TourOptions=""@options"">
    <GuideFlowStep Element=""#step1"" Title=""Welcome!"" Order=""0"">
        <p>This is the first step.</p>
    </GuideFlowStep>

    <GuideFlowStep Element=""#step2"" Title=""Next"" Order=""1"">
        <p>Click here to continue.</p>
    </GuideFlowStep>
</GuideFlowTour>

@code {
    private GuideFlowTour? tour;
    private TourOptions options = new()
    {
        Overlay = true,
        ShowProgress = true,
    };

    private async Task StartTour()
    {
        if (tour != null) await tour.DriveAsync();
    }
}")" />

    <div class="docs-note docs-note--info">
        <strong>💡 Two ways to build tours</strong> GuideFlow supports both <strong>declarative</strong> (Razor markup) and <strong>programmatic</strong> (C# fluent API) approaches. See <a href="docs/programmatic-tour">Programmatic Tour</a> for details.
    </div>

    <h2 id="verify">
        Verify Installation
        <a class="docs-anchor" href="#verify">#</a>
    </h2>

    <p>Run your app and click the "Start Tour" button. You should see the overlay and popover appear. If something doesn't work, check:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>CSS and JS files are correctly referenced in your HTML</li>
        <li><code>AddGuideFlow()</code> is called in <code>Program.cs</code></li>
        <li>Namespaces are imported in <code>_Imports.razor</code></li>
    </ul>

